# moatlog: skills-spec

> The source of truth for how moatlog behavioral skills
> are named and formatted. Used by moatlog skills generate
> as the LLM instruction layer.

## Naming formula

{domain}-{subdomain?}-{outcome}

domain:    top-level area derived from coreFiles paths
           docs/ → docs
           packages/core/ → core
           packages/mcp/ → mcp
           packages/cli/ → cli
           root or mixed → project

subdomain: optional, derived from specific directory
           landing/ → landing
           commands/ → commands
           src/ → omit (too generic)
           components/ → components

outcome:   what this work produces — nouns only, no verbs
           visual changes → styling, visual, layout, tokens
           bug fixes → attribution, handling, resolution
           new features → registration, generation, capture
           refactors → extraction, migration, restructure

Rules:
- 2-3 parts maximum, 4 words maximum total
- Domain nouns only — no verbs (fix, update, add, make,
  create, change, remove, write, build, run, use, get)
- No stop words (please, can, we, the, this, moatlog,
  my, our, you, it, is, a, an, and, or, for, of, to,
  in, with, that, these, those, just, now, also)
- Outcome reflects what changed, not what was requested
- When in doubt: shorter is better

Good names:
  docs-landing-visual
  core-distiller-attribution
  mcp-tool-registration
  cli-merge-resolution
  docs-tokens-styling

Bad names:
  please-update-moatlog (stop words)
  fix-the-landing-page (verbs + stop words)
  you-full (fragments)
  landing-page-updates (verb as outcome)
  moatlog-existing-page (project name + fragments)

## Skill format

Every generated skill must have these sections in order:

FRONTMATTER:
  description: one sentence, type of work this covers
  globs: (empty)
  alwaysApply: false

HEADER:
  # moatlog: {name}
  > Auto-generated from .moatlog/moat.json — do not edit.
  > Regenerate: `moatlog skills generate`

WHEN THIS APPLIES:
  Prefer specific file paths over keywords.
  Good: "When editing docs/app/components/landing/LandingPage.tsx
        or docs/styles/marketing/landing.css"
  Bad:  "When task mentions landing, page, visual"
  Include both files AND outcome keywords for coverage.

CORE FILES:
  Only files appearing in >60% of similar sessions.
  Show confidence percentage.
  Sort by confidence descending.

CO-ACCESS PATTERNS:
  Only pairs with support > 3.
  One line per pair: `file-a` ↔ `file-b` (support: N)
  Omit section if no qualifying pairs.

EXAMPLE TASKS:
  Up to 3 real taskExcerpts, unmodified.
  Prefer shortest excerpts — under 80 characters.
  Never paraphrase or summarize.

BEFORE STARTING:
  Why these files change together — the causal relationship.
  What to check or open first.
  What tends to break when working in this area.
  2-4 sentences maximum. Specific, not generic.
  Good: "globals.css holds the token values that layout.tsx
        applies. Edit tokens.css first, then verify layout.tsx
        renders the changes correctly before touching globals."
  Bad:  "These files are frequently touched together in
        similar tasks."

FOOTER (always append, never from LLM):
  ---
  *Skill generated by moatlog from behavioral data.
  Keep current: `moatlog skills generate` after significant
  work in this area.*

## Quality checklist
Before finalizing a skill:
- [ ] Name follows {domain}-{subdomain?}-{outcome} formula
- [ ] No verbs or stop words in name
- [ ] triggerDescription uses file paths, not just keywords
- [ ] coreFiles only includes >60% confidence files
- [ ] guidance explains WHY files change together, not just
      that they do
- [ ] exampleTasks are real excerpts, not paraphrased
- [ ] footer is present
